{
  "decision_summary": "The chip temperature (89.26°C) exceeds the limit (85.0°C). The previous attempt to increase spreader conductivity failed because it exceeded the upper bound of 500.0 W/(m*K). Since the material property is already at its maximum effective value, the next best lever is to increase the physical size of the heat spreader to improve lateral heat distribution. I will increase the spreader width by 20% (from 0.7 to 0.84), which is within the allowed 1.5x step ratio and fits within the design domain bounds.",
  "changes": [
    {
      "path": "components.2.width",
      "action": "set",
      "old": 0.7,
      "new": 0.84,
      "reason": "Increasing the heat spreader width expands the area available for lateral heat conduction, reducing thermal resistance and lowering the peak chip temperature. This is the primary geometric lever since material conductivity is already maxed out."
    }
  ],
  "expected_effects": [
    "Reduction in chip_max_temperature towards the 85.0°C constraint",
    "More uniform temperature distribution across the top layer",
    "Improved heat flux spreading towards the side boundaries"
  ],
  "risk_notes": [
    "Widening the spreader brings it closer to the left/right domain boundaries; ensure it does not exceed the design domain width of 1.2m (current x0=0.25, new width 0.84 -> x1=1.09, which is safe).",
    "Diminishing returns may occur if the spreader becomes too wide relative to the heat source location.",
    "If this single change is insufficient, subsequent steps may need to combine width increases with base plate conductivity improvements."
  ]
}
